nt Actress]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" |[[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n|''[[Chalo]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Zee Cine Awards|Zee Cine Awards for Favorite Actress]]\n| rowspan=\"5\" |''[[Geetha Govindam]]''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Awards|Sri Kala Sudha Telugu Awards for Best Debut Heroine]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Award for Best Actress]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Award|JFW award - Sensational Actor]]\n|{{Won}}<ref>VBJ JFW Awards 2019: Yet Another Unforgettable Success! https://jfwonline.com/article/vbj-jfw-awards-2019-yet-another-unforgettable-success/</ref>\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor \u2013 South|Filmfare Awards South Best Actress Critics Choice]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[Awards|Behindwoods Gold Medal (Best Actor Critics Choice)]]\n|''[[Dear Comrade]]''\n|{{Won}}<ref name=\"BG\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Rashmika Mandanna}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=8612305|title=Rashmika Mandanna}}\n\n{{SIIMA Award for Best Female D\u00e9butante}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "2409:4060:218b:9552::14a4:c8b0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rashmika_Mandanna"}
{"title_page": "Haitian mythology", "text_new": "{{mergeto|Haitian Vodou|discuss=Talk:Haitian Vodou#Merge proposal|date=November 2019 }}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n[[Haitian Vodou]] is a [[syncretism|syncretic mixture]] of [[Roman Catholic]] rituals developed during the [[French colonial empire|French colonial period]], based on [[Traditional African religion|traditional African beliefs]], with roots in [[Dahomey mythology|Dahomey]], [[Kingdom of Kongo|Kongo]] and [[Yoruba mythology|Yoruba]] traditions, and folkloric influence from the indigenous [[Ta\u00edno people|Taino]] peoples of [[Haiti]]. The [[Loa]], or spirits with whom Vodouisants work and practice, are not gods but servants of the Supreme Creator Bondye (pronounced Bon Dieu). In keeping with the French-Catholic influence of the faith, vodousaints are for the most part monotheists, believing that the Loa are great and powerful forces in the world with whom humans interact and vice versa, resulting in a symbioticthebbodsb iieieoeebobeofbofoeb\nv i  kd djdsk  relationship intended to bring both humans and the Loa back to Bondye. \"Vodou is a religious practice, a faith that points toward an intimate knowledge of God, and offers its practitioners a means to come into communion with the Divine, through an ever evolving paradigm of dance, song and prayers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Vye Zo Komande LaMenfo|first=Mambo|title=Serving the Spirits: The Religion of Vodou|year=2011|publisher=Mambo Vye Zo Komande LaMenfo|location=United States|isbn= 978-0615535241|page=12}}</ref>\n\n== History and origins of Voodooism in Haiti ==\n{{main|Haitian Vodou}}\n\nVoodoo originated from the Animist beliefs of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba tribes]] in Benin,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Weber|first=A. S. |date=December 2018 |title=Haitian Vodou and Ecotheology |url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=134375471&site=ehost-live&authtype=sso&custid=s8992667 |journal=Ecumenical Review |volume=70 |issue=4 |pages=679\u2013694 |url-access=subscription |doi=10.1111/erev.12393}}</ref> but it developed in Haiti during the 18th century among the West Africans slaves who were being evangelized under the French Colonial power. Instead of abandoning their animist beliefs altogether, the slaves chose to affiliate their own traditional representations to the closest personal figures in the Roman Catholic faith for more meaningful purposes. ''The Bondye'', or \u201cBon-Dieu\u201d in French, represents the Supreme monotheist God, the Creator and most importantly, the Unreachable. According to the Animist belief, the only way possible to reach the ''Bondye'' and trigger change in society is by imploring a connection or relationship with the Spirits of the late ancestors which are called ''Loas''.{{cn|date=November 2019}} \n[[File:Voodoo Ceremony in Abomey.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Ritual]]\nThere are in total 180 ''Loas'' in the Voodoo religion, each of them carrying a name and, a specific and exclusive function. For instance, ''\"Guede\"''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scalora |first=Sal |date=1993/03//Mar/Apr93|title=A salute to the spirits |url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=13&sid=394b1efc-2811-4285-9e70-4b5206136ac3@sdc-v-sessmgr02&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ==#AN=9304260020&db=a9h |journal=Americas |volume=45 |issue=2 |pages=26}}</ref> is the spirit of life and death who is assigned to separate the souls and bodies of people when the time comes and also to watch over their graveyards. Through ceremonies of dance and singing, the Haitian Voodoo practitioners invoke these same spirits that in return will possess their bodies and dictate to the people the solution to their social preoccupations. Myths of the Haitian Independence from the French Colonial forces even suggest that this same Spirit, ''\"Guede\"'' entered the body of one of the slaves and cultivated the roots of the Haitian Revolutionary ideologies.{{cn|date=November 2019}} This is one of the reasons why Voodoists consider their faith as a way of escape not only from Slavery but also from their personal issues.{{cn|date=November 2019}} \n\nAlthough this is a positive way of picturing this folkloric religion, most believers of Catholicism reject Voodooism that they say is a \"pact with Satan\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Schmidt |first=David| date=2011-02-04 |title=Making sense of hell on Earth |<!--url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=58621878&site=ehost-live&authtype=sso&custid=s8992667--> |journal=National Catholic Reporter |volume=47|issue=8|pages=20\u201320}}</ref> that is till today the main source of misery, poverty and natural disaster in Haiti.\n\n==Related notions==\n* Asagwe - Haitian Vodou dancing used to honor the Loa.\n* Avalou - (\"supplication\") Haitian Vodou dance.\n* Coco macaque - Haitian Vodou implement. It is a stick, which is supposed to be able to walk on its own. The owner of a coco macaque can send it on errands. If it is used to hit an enemy, the enemy will die before the dawn.\n* Gangan, [[Houngan]] - Haitian priests. They lead the peoples in dancing, drumming, and singing to invoke the Loa.\n* [[Ghede]] - family of spirits related to death and fertility.\n* [[Guinee]] - Haitian afterlife. It is also where life began and the home of their spirits.\n* [[Loa]] - Haitian Vodou spirit.\n* [[Mambo (Vodou)|Mambo]] - Haitian priestess who, together with the Houngan, leads the Vodou rituals and invokes the Loa.\n* [[Paquet congo]] - charms made of organic matter wrapped in cloth, intended to rouse the Loa.\n* [[Petro loa|Petro]] - aggressive and warlike family of spirits\n* [[Rada loa|Rada]] - old, benefic family of spirits\n* [[Tonton Macoute (disambiguation)|Tonton Macoute]], a Haitian mythological phrase meaning \"bogey man\" (literally: \"Uncle [[Sack Man|Bagman]]\")\n* Ville au Camp - (\"House in the Fields\") the underwater capital of the Loa\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Haitian Vodou]]\n* [[Culture of Haiti]]\n* [[Religion in Haiti]]\n* [[Haitian art]]\n* [[Veve]], a religious symbol commonly used in Vodou and [[Palo (religion)|Palo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060516165730/http://www.webster.edu/~corbetre/haiti/voodoo/biglist.htm List of Vodou Loa]\n\n[[Category:Haitian culture]]\n[[Category:Caribbean mythology]]\n[[Category:Haitian Vodou]]\n[[Category:Religion in Haiti]]\n", "text_old": "{{mergeto|Haitian Vodou|discuss=Talk:Haitian Vodou#Merge proposal|date=November 2019 }}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n[[Haitian Vodou]] is a [[syncretism|syncretic mixture]] of [[Roman Catholic]] rituals developed during the [[French colonial empire|French colonial period]], based on [[Traditional African religion|traditional African beliefs]], with roots in [[Dahomey mythology|Dahomey]], [[Kingdom of Kongo|Kongo]] and [[Yoruba mythology|Yoruba]] traditions, and folkloric influence from the indigenous [[Ta\u00edno people|Taino]] peoples of [[Haiti]]. The [[Loa]], or spirits with whom Vodouisants work and practice, are not gods but servants of the Supreme Creator Bondye (pronounced Bon Dieu). In keeping with the French-Catholic influence of the faith, vodousaints are for the most part monotheists, believing that the Loa are great and powerful forces in the world with whom humans interact and vice versa, resulting in a symbiotic relationship intended to bring both humans and the Loa back to Bondye. \"Vodou is a religious practice, a faith that points toward an intimate knowledge of God, and offers its practitioners a means to come into communion with the Divine, through an ever evolving paradigm of dance, song and prayers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Vye Zo Komande LaMenfo|first=Mambo|title=Serving the Spirits: The Religion of Vodou|year=2011|publisher=Mambo Vye Zo Komande LaMenfo|location=United States|isbn= 978-0615535241|page=12}}</ref>\n\n== History and origins of Voodooism in Haiti ==\n{{main|Haitian Vodou}}\n\nVoodoo originated from the Animist beliefs of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba tribes]] in Benin,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Weber|first=A. S. |date=December 2018 |title=Haitian Vodou and Ecotheology |url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=134375471&site=ehost-live&authtype=sso&custid=s8992667 |journal=Ecumenical Review |volume=70 |issue=4 |pages=679\u2013694 |url-access=subscription |doi=10.1111/erev.12393}}</ref> but it developed in Haiti during the 18th century among the West Africans slaves who were being evangelized under the French Colonial power. Instead of abandoning their animist beliefs altogether, the slaves chose to affiliate their own traditional representations to the closest personal figures in the Roman Catholic faith for more meaningful purposes. ''The Bondye'', or \u201cBon-Dieu\u201d in French, represents the Supreme monotheist God, the Creator and most importantly, the Unreachable. According to the Animist belief, the only way possible to reach the ''Bondye'' and trigger change in society is by imploring a connection or relationship with the Spirits of the late ancestors which are called ''Loas''.{{cn|date=November 2019}} \n[[File:Voodoo Ceremony in Abomey.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Ritual]]\nThere are in total 180 ''Loas'' in the Voodoo religion, each of them carrying a name and, a specific and exclusive function. For instance, ''\"Guede\"''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scalora |first=Sal |date=1993/03//Mar/Apr93|title=A salute to the spirits |url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=13&sid=394b1efc-2811-4285-9e70-4b5206136ac3@sdc-v-sessmgr02&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ==#AN=9304260020&db=a9h |journal=Americas |volume=45 |issue=2 |pages=26}}</ref> is the spirit of life and death who is assigned to separate the souls and bodies of people when the time comes and also to watch over their graveyards. Through ceremonies of dance and singing, the Haitian Voodoo practitioners invoke these same spirits that in return will possess their bodies and dictate to the people the solution to their social preoccupations. Myths of the Haitian Independence from the French Colonial forces even suggest that this same Spirit, ''\"Guede\"'' entered the body of one of the slaves and cultivated the roots of the Haitian Revolutionary ideologies.{{cn|date=November 2019}} This is one of the reasons why Voodoists consider their faith as a way of escape not only from Slavery but also from their personal issues.{{cn|date=November 2019}} \n\nAlthough this is a positive way of picturing this folkloric religion, most believers of Catholicism reject Voodooism that they say is a \"pact with Satan\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Schmidt |first=David| date=2011-02-04 |title=Making sense of hell on Earth |<!--url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=58621878&site=ehost-live&authtype=sso&custid=s8992667--> |journal=National Catholic Reporter |volume=47|issue=8|pages=20\u201320}}</ref> that is till today the main source of misery, poverty and natural disaster in Haiti.\n\n==Related notions==\n* Asagwe - Haitian Vodou dancing used to honor the Loa.\n* Avalou - (\"supplication\") Haitian Vodou dance.\n* Coco macaque - Haitian Vodou implement. It is a stick, which is supposed to be able to walk on its own. The owner of a coco macaque can send it on errands. If it is used to hit an enemy, the enemy will die before the dawn.\n* Gangan, [[Houngan]] - Haitian priests. They lead the peoples in dancing, drumming, and singing to invoke the Loa.\n* [[Ghede]] - family of spirits related to death and fertility.\n* [[Guinee]] - Haitian afterlife. It is also where life began and the home of their spirits.\n* [[Loa]] - Haitian Vodou spirit.\n* [[Mambo (Vodou)|Mambo]] - Haitian priestess who, together with the Houngan, leads the Vodou rituals and invokes the Loa.\n* [[Paquet congo]] - charms made of organic matter wrapped in cloth, intended to rouse the Loa.\n* [[Petro loa|Petro]] - aggressive and warlike family of spirits\n* [[Rada loa|Rada]] - old, benefic family of spirits\n* [[Tonton Macoute (disambiguation)|Tonton Macoute]], a Haitian mythological phrase meaning \"bogey man\" (literally: \"Uncle [[Sack Man|Bagman]]\")\n* Ville au Camp - (\"House in the Fields\") the underwater capital of the Loa\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Haitian Vodou]]\n* [[Culture of Haiti]]\n* [[Religion in Haiti]]\n* [[Haitian art]]\n* [[Veve]], a religious symbol commonly used in Vodou and [[Palo (religion)|Palo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060516165730/http://www.webster.edu/~corbetre/haiti/voodoo/biglist.htm List of Vodou Loa]\n\n[[Category:Haitian culture]]\n[[Category:Caribbean mythology]]\n[[Category:Haitian Vodou]]\n[[Category:Religion in Haiti]]\n", "name_user": "2601:580:4400:3cda:b5dd:2d09:81d5:dea2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haitian_mythology"}
{"title_page": "List of Interstate Highways in New York", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{infobox state highway system\n|shields=[[File:I-90.svg|70px]] [[File:I-390 (long).svg|88px]]\n|caption=Standard Interstate shields in New York\n|map=NYInterstates.svg\n|map_notes=Map of Interstate Highways in the state of New York as of June 2002\n|formed=\n|interstate=Interstate&nbsp;X (I-X)\n|us=U.S. Route&nbsp;X (US&nbsp;X)\n|state=New York State Route&nbsp;X (NY&nbsp;X)\n|links=NY\n}}\nThere are 31&nbsp;[[Interstate Highways]]\u20149&nbsp;main routes and 22&nbsp;auxiliary routes\u2014that exist entirely or partially in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]. In New York, Interstate Highways are mostly maintained by the [[New York State Department of Transportation]] (NYSDOT), with some exceptions. Unlike in some other states, Interstate Highways in New York are not directly referenced by NYSDOT with their number; instead, the letter \"I\" is suffixed to the number of the route on [[reference marker (New York)|reference marker]]s and in internal documents. On the surface, there appears to be numerical duplication between several Interstate Highways and state routes\u2014such as [[Interstate 86 (east)|I-86]] (I-86) and [[New York State Route 86|NY&nbsp;86]]\u2014but the \"I\" suffix that is appended to Interstate Highway numbers allows the Interstate Highway and state route to co-exist (\"86I\" versus \"86\", respectively). \n\nThere are a combined {{convert|1673|mi|0}} of Interstate Highways within New York, which handles about 19 percent of vehicle travel in New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Key Facts About New York's Interstate Highway System |publisher=Tripnet.org |accessdate=June 15, 2008 |url=http://www.tripnet.org/NewYorkInterstateFactSheet062906.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327023227/http://www.tripnet.org/NewYorkInterstateFactSheet062906.pdf |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref> At approximately {{convert|0.50|mi|2}}, [[Interstate 78 in New York|I-78]] is the shortest main Interstate Highway, while [[Interstate 90 in New York|I-90]] is the longest, spanning {{convert|385.88|mi|2}} within New York. [[Interstate 878|I-878]], located in [[Queens]], is the shortest active route in the [[Interstate Highway System]] at {{convert|0.7|mi|2}}.\n\nSmall portions of [[Interstate 278|I-278]] in [[New York City]] are maintained by local authorities rather than the state transportation agency.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/regional-offices/region11/general-info/built-and-unbuilt-arterial-system |title=Region 11 (New York City) Built and Unbuilt Arterial System |publisher=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref> In addition, parts of [[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]], [[Interstate 287|I-287]], I-90, [[Interstate 190 (New York)|I-190]], and [[Interstate 95 in New York|I-95]] are part of the [[New York State Thruway]] system and thus are maintained by the [[New York State Thruway Authority]].\n\nThe \"From\" column indicates the southern or western terminus of the route; likewise, the \"To\" column indicates the northern or eastern terminus of the route. The \"mi\" and \"km\" columns give the length of the route in miles and kilometers, respectively. Designations shaded in dark gray are numbers that were once assigned to a highway but are no longer in use, or numbers that have been proposed for a future highway.\n\n==Main routes==\n{{routelist top|length_ref=\n<ref name=\"length\" />}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=78\n|length_mi=0.90\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 78 in New Jersey|I-78]] at [[Manhattan]]\n|terminus_b=[[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal Street]] in Manhattan\n|established=1961\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i78\" />\n|notes=I-78 crosses the [[Hudson River]] from [[New Jersey]] via the [[Holland Tunnel]] and ends at the tunnel plaza in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref name=\"des\">{{cite map |title=New York State Map |publisher=[[American Map Company|American Map]] |year=2007 |cartography=American Map}}</ref>\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=81\n|length_mi=183.62\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 81 in Pennsylvania|I-81]] at the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania border|Pennsylvania state line]] in [[Kirkwood, New York|Kirkwood]]\n|terminus_b=[[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] at [[Thousand Islands]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|notes=I-81 crosses the Pennsylvania state line south of [[Binghamton (city), New York|Binghamton]] and heads through [[central New York]] and the [[North Country, New York|North Country]] to the Thousand Islands, where it becomes [[Ontario Highway&nbsp;137]] at the Canada\u2013US border. Along the way, I-81 passes through the cities of [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] and [[Watertown, New York|Watertown]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=84\n|length_mi=71.46\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 84 in Pennsylvania|I-84]] at the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania border|Pennsylvania state line]] in [[Port Jervis, New York|Port Jervis]]\n|terminus_b=[[Connecticut]] state line at [[Southeast, New York|Southeast]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|notes=I-84 crosses the New York\u2013Pennsylvania state line near the point where New York, Pennsylvania, and [[New Jersey]] meet in the vicinity of Port Jervis. It heads generally east\u2013west across [[Orange County, New York|Orange]], [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess]] and [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam]] counties to the Connecticut state line east of [[Brewster, New York|Brewster]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=86\n|length_mi=215.18\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 86 (Pennsylvania-New York)|I-86]] at the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania border|Pennsylvania state line]] in [[Mina, New York|Mina]]\n|terminus_b=[[New York State Route 17|NY 17]] in [[Waverly, Tioga County, New York|Waverly]]<!--primary segment-->\n|established=1999\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i86\" />\n|notes=I-86, known as the [[Interstate 86 (Pennsylvania\u2013New York)|Southern Tier Expressway]], heads east\u2013west across the Southern Tier from the Pennsylvania state line west of [[Findley Lake, New York|Findley Lake]] to [[New York State Route 352|NY&nbsp;352]] east of downtown Elmira.<ref name=\"length\" /> A second section of I-86 exists in central [[Broome County, New York|Broome County]], occupying part of an expressway known as the Quickway.<ref name=\"2009map\" /> Both pieces of I-86 will eventually be part of a continuous route extending from [[Erie, Pennsylvania]], to [[Harriman, New York|Harriman]]. The I-86 designation is being extended eastward as improvements are made to the existing [[New York State Route 17|NY&nbsp;17]] expressway.\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=87\n|length_mi=333.90\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 278|I-278]] in [[The Bronx]]\n|terminus_b=[[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] at [[Champlain (town), New York|Champlain]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|notes=I-87 extends from [[The Bronx]] approach to the [[Triborough Bridge]] in New York City to the Canada\u2013US border near Champlain, where it connects with [[Quebec Autoroute&nbsp;15]], the [[Decarie Expressway]] of [[Montreal]]. The portion of I-87 from the New York City line to [[Albany, New York|Albany]] is part of the New York State Thruway mainline; at Albany, I-87 leaves the Thruway and becomes the [[Interstate 87 (New York)|Adirondack Northway]]. Aside from Albany, I-87 also serves [[Kingston (city), New York|Kingston NY]], [[Glens Falls, New York|Glens Falls]], and [[Plattsburgh (city), New York|Plattsburgh]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=88\n|length_mi=117.70\n|terminus_a=[[#I0081|I-81]] in [[Chenango, New York|Chenango]]\n|terminus_b=[[#I0090|I-90]]/[[New York State Thruway]] in [[Rotterdam (town), New York|Rotterdam]]\n|established=1968\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i88\" />\n|notes=I-88 serves as a connector between I-81 near [[Binghamton, New York|Binghamton]] and the New York State Thruway (I-90) near [[Schenectady, New York|Schenectady]]. It parallels [[New York State Route 7|NY&nbsp;7]] between the two cities and passes through the city of [[Oneonta (city), New York|Oneonta]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=90\n|length_mi=386.69\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 90 in Pennsylvania|I-90]] at the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania border|Pennsylvania state line]] in [[Ripley, New York|Ripley]]\n|terminus_b=[[Massachusetts Turnpike|I-90]]/[[Massachusetts Turnpike|Mass Pike]] at the [[Massachusetts]] state line in [[Canaan, New York|Canaan]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|notes=I-90 travels from the Pennsylvania state line at [[Ripley, New York|Ripley]] to the [[Massachusetts]] border at Canaan. The vast majority of I-90 in New York is part of the New York State Thruway system; the only segment that is not part of the system is a {{convert|20|mi|km|sing=on}} portion in the city of [[Albany, New York|Albany]] and its eastern suburbs. Aside from Albany, I-90 also serves [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] (via [[Interstate 490 (New York)|I-490]]), [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], and [[Utica, New York|Utica]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=90N\n|length_mi=27.75\n|terminus_a=[[#I0090|I-90]]/[[New York State Thruway]] in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]\n|terminus_b=[[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] at [[Lewiston (town), New York|Lewiston]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|decommissioned=1959\n|decommissioned_ref=<ref name=\"i190\" />\n|notes=I-90N was the original designation for what is now [[Interstate 190 (New York)|I-190]] in [[western New York]]. It was renumbered to I-190 in 1959.<ref name=\"i190\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=95\n|length_mi=23.44\n|terminus_a=[[Interstate 95 in New Jersey|I-95]]/[[U.S. Route 1 in New Jersey|US 1]]/[[U.S. Route 9 in New Jersey|US 9]]/[[U.S. Route 46|US 46]] at the [[New Jersey]] state line in [[Manhattan]]\n|terminus_b=[[Interstate 95 in Connecticut|I-95]]/[[Connecticut Turnpike]] at the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Port Chester, New York|Port Chester]]\n|established=1957\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1957mapi\" />\n|notes=I-95 extends from the [[George Washington Bridge]] over the [[Hudson River]] (where it crosses from New Jersey into [[New York City]]) to the Connecticut state line at Port Chester. It passes through New York City on the [[Trans-Manhattan Expressway|Trans-Manhattan]] and [[Cross Bronx Expressway]]s.<ref name=\"des\" /> The portion of I-95 from the [[Pelham Parkway (road)|Pelham Parkway]] in the Bronx to the Connecticut state line is known as the [[New England Thruway]] and is part of the New York State Thruway system.<ref name=\"thruway\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=99\n|length_mi=12.89\n|terminus_a=I-99/[[U.S. Route 15 in Pennsylvania|US 15]] at the [[New York\u2013Pennsylvania border|Pennsylvania state line]] in [[Lindley, New York|Lindley]]\n|terminus_b=[[#I0086|I-86]]/[[U.S. Route 15 in New York|US 15]]/[[New York State Route 17|NY 17]] in [[Painted Post, New York|Painted Post]]\n|established=2014\n|established_ref=<ref name=I99NY>{{cite news|last1=[Staff writer] |title=Corning area now has 2 interstates; U.S. 15 designated I-99 to Pa. border |url=http://www.stargazette.com/article/20140627/NEWS01/306270011/Corning-area-now-has-2-interstates-U-S-15-designated-I-99-to-Pa-border |accessdate=28 June 2014 |work=Star-Gazette |publisher=Sherman M. Bodner |date=27 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715105338/http://www.stargazette.com/article/20140627/NEWS01/306270011/Corning-area-now-has-2-interstates-U-S-15-designated-I-99-to-Pa-border?nclick_check=1 |archivedate=15 July 2014 }}</ref>\n|notes=I-99 runs north from Pennsylvania along [[U.S. Route 15 in New York|US&nbsp;15]] to I-86 near Corning.\n}}\n{{routelist bottom|keys=former}}\n\n==Auxiliary routes==\n{{routelist top|length_ref=<ref name=\"length\" />}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=190\n|terminus_a=[[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]\n|terminus_b=[[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] at [[Lewiston (town), New York|Lewiston]]\n|length_mi=28.09\n|established=1959\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i190\" />\n|notes=I-190 is a spur connecting the [[New York State Thruway]] ([[Interstate 90 in New York|I-90]]) at exit&nbsp;53 near Buffalo to the Canada\u2013United States border at Lewiston, north of [[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]].<ref name=\"des\" /> The portion of I-190 south of [[New York State Route 384|NY&nbsp;384]] is part of the [[New York State Thruway]] system.<ref name=\"thruway\" /> I-190 is the only [[three-digit Interstate Highway]] that reaches the Canadian border.<ref name=\"i190\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=278\n|terminus_a=[[New Jersey]] line at [[Staten Island]]\n|terminus_b=[[The Bronx]]\n|length_mi=33.85\n|established=1960\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1960map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-278 crosses from New Jersey to New York by way of the [[Goethals Bridge]] over the [[Arthur Kill]] at [[Staten Island]]. It passes through all five boroughs of [[New York City]] (technically entering [[Manhattan]] when it passes over [[Wards Island]] on the [[Triborough Bridge]]) before coming to an end at the [[Bruckner Interchange]] in the Bronx.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=281\n|terminus_a=[[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]]\n|terminus_b=[[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]]\n|length_mi=9.45<!--modern I-481 from I-81 to I-90-->\n|established=1963\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1962map\" /><ref name=\"1963map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|decommissioned=1970\n|decommissioned_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\">{{cite book |url=http://www.greaternyroads.info/pdfs/state70.pdf |title=Official Description of Touring Routes in New York State |author=[[State of New York Department of Transportation]] |date=January 1, 1970 |format=PDF |accessdate=August 31, 2010}}</ref>\n|notes=I-281 was a connector highway between [[Interstate 81 in New York|I-81]] and I-90 that passed through the southeastern suburbs of Syracuse. It was renumbered to I-481 in 1970, possibly to avoid confusion with [[New York State Route 281|NY&nbsp;281]], a highway that parallels I-81 some miles south of Syracuse.<ref name=\"1970log\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=287\n|terminus_a=[[New Jersey]] line at [[Suffern, New York|Suffern]]\n|terminus_b=[[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]\n|length_mi=30.47\n|established=1960\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1960map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-287 crosses the New Jersey border into New York near Suffern and heads generally southeastward across [[Rockland County, New York|Rockland]] and [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] counties to [[Interstate 95 in New York|I-95]] in [[Rye (city), New York|Rye]]. Most of I-287 in Rockland County [[overlap (road)|overlap]]s with [[Interstate 87 (New York)|I-87]] and all of I-287 east of Suffern is part of the New York State Thruway system.<ref name=\"des\" /><ref name=\"thruway\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=290\n|terminus_a=[[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda]]\n|terminus_b=[[Amherst, New York|Amherst]]\n|length_mi=9.45\n|established=1962\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1962map\" /><ref name=\"1961map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-290 is a connector between I-190 in the town of Tonawanda and the New York State Thruway (I-90) near [[Williamsville, New York|Williamsville]]. It serves as a northern bypass of [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=295\n|terminus_a=[[The Bronx]]\n|terminus_b=[[Queens]]\n|length_mi=9.79\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\" />\n|notes=I-295 is a connector route within [[New York City]]. It travels from the [[Bruckner Interchange]] in the Bronx to the [[Grand Central Parkway]] in Queens. It crosses the [[East River]] by way of the tolled [[Throgs Neck Bridge]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=390\n|terminus_a=[[Avoca (town), New York|Avoca]]\n|terminus_b=[[Gates, New York|Gates]]\n|length_mi=76.42\n|established=1973\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1972map\" /><ref name=\"1973map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-390 extends from the [[Interstate 86 (Pennsylvania\u2013New York)|Southern Tier Expressway]] ([[Interstate 86 (Pennsylvania\u2013New York)|I-86]] and [[New York State Route 17|NY&nbsp;17]]) in the [[Southern Tier]] town of Avoca to I-490 just west of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]]. I-390 connects to I-90 (the New York State Thruway) in [[Henrietta, New York|Henrietta]], a southern suburb of Rochester.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=478\n|terminus_a=[[Brooklyn]]\n|terminus_b=[[Manhattan]]\n|length_mi=2.41\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\" /><ref name=\"1973map\" /><!--it's unclear whether or not the 1970 log description is the current route or not-->\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-478's entire length consists of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]] and its approaches. Its south end is at I-278, and its north end is at [[New York State Route 9A|NY&nbsp;9A]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=481\n|terminus_a=[[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]]\n|terminus_b=[[North Syracuse, New York|North Syracuse]]\n|length_mi=14.96\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\" />\n|notes=I-481 leaves I-81 south of Syracuse and rejoins its parent in North Syracuse. I-81 serves downtown Syracuse while I-481 bypasses the city to the east, passing through the Syracuse suburbs of [[Jamesville, New York|Jamesville]] and [[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]] along the way.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=487\n|terminus_a=[[The Bronx]]\n|terminus_b=[[Beacon, New York|Beacon]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|decommissioned=yes\n|decommissioned_ref=\n|notes=I-487 was a proposed designation for the [[Hudson River Expressway]], a highway that would have run through the [[Hudson Valley]] between the Bronx and Beacon. The project was cancelled by 1971.<ref name=\"i487\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=490\n|terminus_a=[[Le Roy (town), New York|Le Roy]]\n|terminus_b=[[Victor (town), New York|Victor]]\n|length_mi=37.62\n|established=1961\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1960map\" /><ref name=\"1961map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-490 is a loop route off the New York State Thruway (I-90) between the town of Le Roy and the town of Victor. I-90 bypasses the city of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] to the south while I-490 serves the city's suburbs and Rochester itself.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=495\n|terminus_a=[[Manhattan]]\n|terminus_b=[[Riverhead (town), New York|Riverhead]]\n|length_mi=70.99\n|established=1958\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i495\" />\n|notes=I-495, better known as the Long Island Expressway or LIE, extends across [[Long Island]] from the western portal of the [[Queens Midtown Tunnel]] in Manhattan to [[Riverhead (CDP), New York|Riverhead]], [[Suffolk County, New York|Suffolk County]].<ref name=\"des\" /> There is a gap in the designation between I-278 and I-678, where it is designated in between as NY 495.<ref name=\"2017log\"/>\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=587\n|terminus_a=[[Kingston, New York|Kingston]]\n|terminus_b=Kingston\n|length_mi=1.23\n|established=1960\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i587\" />\n|notes=I-587 is a short spur linking downtown Kingston to the [[New York State Thruway]] (I-87) at exit&nbsp;19 northwest of the city. It is entirely concurrent with [[New York State Route 28|NY&nbsp;28]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=590\n|terminus_a=[[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton]]\n|terminus_b=[[Rochester, New York|Rochester]]\n|length_mi=4.91\n|established=1980\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"2009log\">{{cite book|url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2012%20tour-bk.pdf |title=Official Description of Highway Touring Routes, Bicycling Touring Routes, Scenic Byways, & Commemorative/Memorial Designations in New York State |author=New York State Department of Transportation |date=January 2012 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729075940/https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2012%20tour-bk.pdf |archivedate=July 29, 2013 }}</ref>\n|notes=I-590 serves as a connector between I-390 in Brighton and I-490 in Rochester (at the [[Can of Worms (interchange)|Can of Worms]]).<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=678\n|terminus_a=[[Queens]]\n|terminus_b=[[The Bronx]]\n|length_mi=14.68\n|established=1965\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1964map\" /><ref name=\"1965map1\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-678 runs entirely within two [[borough (New York City)|borough]]s of [[New York City]]: Queens and the Bronx. The highway begins at the [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] and ends at the [[Bruckner Interchange]] in the Bronx.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=684\n|terminus_a=[[White Plains, New York|White Plains]]\n|terminus_b=[[Southeast, New York|Southeast]]\n|length_mi=28.43<!--includes small portion in CT-->\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\" />\n|notes=I-684 connects I-287 in White Plains to [[Interstate 84 in New York|I-84]] near [[Brewster, New York|Brewster]]. A small portion of the route is located in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=687\n|terminus_a=[[Albany, New York|Albany]]\n|terminus_b=[[Colonie (town), New York|Colonie]]\n|length_mi=4.6\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|decommissioned=yes\n|decommissioned_ref=\n|notes=I-687 was a proposed designation for a connector between I-90 and I-87 in northern Albany. The expressway was never constructed due to a lack of funding. I-687 was removed from local and national highway plans in the 1970s.<ref name=\"i687\" /> The I-687 designation is currently resevered.<ref name=\"2017log\">{{cite book |url=https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2017%20tour-bk.pdf |title=Official Description of Highway Touring Routes, Bicycling Touring Routes, Scenic Byways, & Commemorative/Memorial Designations in New York State |author=[[New York State Department of Transportation]] |date=January 2017 |format=PDF |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=690\n|terminus_a=[[Van Buren, New York|Van Buren]]\n|terminus_b=[[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]]\n|length_mi=13.61\n|established=1962\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1962map\" /><ref name=\"1961map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-690 travels southeast from exit&nbsp;39 on the [[New York State Thruway]] (I-90) in Van Buren and passes through the western suburbs of [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] before heading east through the city itself and terminating in DeWitt, where it merges into I-481. I-690 serves the [[New York State Fairgrounds]] by way of exits&nbsp;5\u20137.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=695\n|terminus_a=[[The Bronx]]\n|terminus_b=The Bronx\n|length_mi=1.77\n|established=1986\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i695\" />\n|notes=I-695 is a short connector route in the Bronx between I-95 ([[Bruckner Expressway]]) and I-295 ([[Cross Bronx Expressway]]) near the [[Throgs Neck Bridge]].<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=781\n|terminus_a=[[Pamelia, New York|Pamelia]]\n|terminus_b=[[Le Ray, New York|Le Ray]]\n|length_mi=4.74\n|established=2009\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"i781\" />\n|notes=I-781 is a connector north of [[Watertown (city), New York|Watertown]] between I-81 and [[Fort Drum, New York|Fort Drum]].<ref name=\"i781\" /> It was completed in 2012.<ref name=\"i781open\">{{cite news |title=Fort Drum connector road officially open |url=http://watertown.ynn.com/content/top_stories/619597/fort-drum-connector-road-officially-open/ |accessdate=December 11, 2012 |newspaper=[[YNN Central New York]] |date=December 6, 2012 |location=[[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse, NY]]}}</ref>\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=787\n|terminus_a=[[Albany, New York|Albany]]\n|terminus_b=[[Troy, New York|Troy]]\n|length_mi=10.17\n|established=1965\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1964map\" /><ref name=\"1965map2\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-787 is a spur leading from New York State Thruway exit&nbsp;23 southwest of downtown Albany to the city of Troy north of Albany. In between, I-787 passes through downtown Albany.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=790\n|terminus_a=[[Utica, New York|Utica]]\n|terminus_b=Utica\n|length_mi=2.06\n|established=1961\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1961map\" /><ref name=\"1965map1\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-790 is a short connector route linking downtown Utica to exit&nbsp;31 of the New York State Thruway (I-90) northeast of the city.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=878\n|terminus_a=[[Queens]]\n|terminus_b=Queens\n|length_mi=0.70\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\"/>\n|notes=I-878 is an unsigned designation for the portion of [[New York State Route 878|NY&nbsp;878]] from I-678 ([[Van Wyck Expressway]]) east to the [[JFK Expressway]]. It is the shortest [[List of auxiliary Interstate Highways|three-digit Interstate Highway]] in the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref name=\"i878\" /> I-878 is not shown in the traffic logs.\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=890\n|terminus_a=[[Rotterdam (town), New York|Rotterdam]]\n|terminus_b=[[Guilderland, New York|Guilderland]]\n|length_mi=9.14\n|established=1962\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1962map\" /><ref name=\"1961map\" />\n|notes=I-890 is a loop route off the New York State Thruway (I-90) between Gilderland and Rotterdam. While the Thruway bypasses the city of [[Schenectady, New York|Schenectady]] to the south, I-890 directly serves it.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=895\n|terminus_a=[[The Bronx]]\n|terminus_b=The Bronx\n|length_mi=1.35\n|established=1970\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1970log\" />\n|decommissioned=2017\n|notes=I-895 was a short freeway in the Bronx, linking the [[Bruckner Expressway]] (I-278) to the [[Cross Bronx Expressway]] (I-95); renumbered as NY 895.<ref name=\"des\" />\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NY\n|type=I\n|route=990\n|terminus_a=[[Amherst, New York|Amherst]]\n|terminus_b=Amherst\n|length_mi=6.29\n|established=1981\n|established_ref=<ref name=\"1981map\" /><ref name=\"1985map\" />\n|circa_established=yes\n|notes=I-990 is a spur in the Buffalo suburb of Amherst that leads from I-290 to [[New York State Route 263|NY&nbsp;263]] in northern [[Erie County, New York|Erie County]].<ref name=\"des\" /> It is the highest numbered route in the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref name=\"i990\" />\n}}\n{{routelist bottom|keys=former}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|U.S. roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"length\">https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/NYSDOT_Traffic_Data_Report_2014.pdf</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1957mapi\">{{cite map |publisher=[[Ame